Brad Pitt.

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:50.630
Or if Cole Porter was outselling
Lady Gaga, which

00:02:50.630 --> 00:02:52.960
needless to say, no one
expects would happen.

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:53.690
Right?

00:02:53.690 --> 00:02:55.670
And what's interesting is, if
you look even at the packaged

00:02:55.670 --> 00:02:56.390
goods business--

00:02:56.390 --> 00:02:57.580
you look at something like

00:02:57.580 --> 00:02:59.030
Campbell's Soup, for instance--

00:02:59.030 --> 00:03:01.675
and their packaged good
business, their soup, has

00:03:01.675 --> 00:03:07.850
changed more as a product than
has "Monopoly." And that is

00:03:07.850 --> 00:03:09.730
one thing that gave us pause
as we were starting the

00:03:09.730 --> 00:03:12.280
business, but that was one of
the things that attracted us

00:03:12.280 --> 00:03:13.310
to that business.

00:03:13.310 --> 00:03:16.440
And the reason that it attracted
us to the business

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:20.110
is because in another life, my
partner and I used to run high

00:03:20.110 --> 00:03:21.000
tech companies.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.160
I ran a photographics company in
the late '80s, early '90s,

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:27.660
called Ray Dream, which was
doing photographic software.

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:30.510
And while that was fun, and we
learned a lot, one thing that

00:03:30.510 --> 00:03:33.100
I felt frustrated with is, we
sold that company to a company

00:03:33.100 --> 00:03:36.190
called Fractal Design, which
had just gone public.

00:03:36.190 --> 00:03:39.050
And two years later, I was
offered to buy back that

00:03:39.050 --> 00:03:41.190
company, which I had sold
to them for over $50

00:03:41.190 --> 00:03:43.460
million, for $1.

00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:46.120
And I politely declined, and I
was right to decline because a

00:03:46.120 --> 00:03:47.470
friend of mine who [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:47.470 --> 00:03:48.870
lost his shirt.

00:03:48.870 --> 00:03:51.780
But what was frustrating about
that was, that while you can

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:54.300
make money and learn things,
there's very few companies--

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:56.410
and Google is one of the
exceptions, so I think you

00:03:56.410 --> 00:03:57.980
guys are lucky--

00:03:57.980 --> 00:04:02.110
that can really stand the test
of time on the digital side.

00:04:02.110 --> 00:04:03.910
And so that's one thing that
was very attractive to us

00:04:03.910 --> 00:04:05.140
about the board game business.

00:04:05.140 --> 00:04:08.150
Now, the flip side of that, of
course, is that means the

00:04:08.150 --> 00:04:11.240
incumbents, the "Monopolies" of
the world, if they've been

00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:13.010
on top for the last 80
years, how are you

00:04:13.010 --> 00:04:14.070
going to displace them?

00:04:14.070 --> 00:04:17.709
Or how are you going to carve
your own place in the sun in

00:04:17.709 --> 00:04:18.880
that market?

00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:20.640
And that's an interesting
challenge.

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:23.190
So when we started the company,
we had a theory, and

00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:24.210
we had a bet.

00:04:24.210 --> 00:04:29.690
The theory was that the main
reason why those games can

00:04:29.690 --> 00:04:32.990
stand for so long at the top is
not because they have the

00:04:32.990 --> 00:04:34.710
best game design out there.

00:04:34.710 --> 00:04:37.630
I mean clearly, since
"Monopoly," game design has

00:04:37.630 --> 00:04:38.370
evolved a lot.

00:04:38.370 --> 00:04:40.570
You have games now, like
"Settlers of Catan" and

00:04:40.570 --> 00:04:44.430
"Ticket to Ride," that arguably
are better from a

00:04:44.430 --> 00:04:46.230
plain game design standpoint.

00:04:46.230 --> 00:04:48.890
So how come "Monopoly"
is still on top?

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:51.930
Well, we think the reason that
is if we were to take people

00:04:51.930 --> 00:04:53.830
up front that are in this room,
or anywhere else in the

00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:57.100
world, for that matter, and I
was to invite some of you to

00:04:57.100 --> 00:04:59.810
my house to play a game, no
matter what's the game.

00:04:59.810 --> 00:05:01.360
Let's just assume it's
a good game.

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:03.220
We'll play together.

00:05:03.220 --> 00:05:05.840
Eight out of 10 of you at least,
if not more, will have

00:05:05.840 --> 00:05:06.670
a great time.

00:05:06.670 --> 00:05:09.010
And at the end of the evening,
you'll say, that was great.

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:11.160
Where can I go and
buy this game?

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:14.720
Now, I take the exact same
sample of people, so the exact

00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:17.250
same people, and I give you a
copy of the same game we were

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:20.430
playing that night in
the shrink wrap.

00:05:20.430 --> 00:05:23.050
And I call you back in six
months, and I ask you how you

00:05:23.050 --> 00:05:24.110
like the game.

00:05:24.110 --> 00:05:27.400
And a large number of you won't
even have cracked the

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:29.204
shrink wrap open.

00:05:29.204 --> 00:05:30.020
OK?

00:05:30.020 --> 00:05:31.820
And so that was the theory.

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:34.060
The theory was that while people
enjoy playing board

00:05:34.060 --> 00:05:38.830
games, they don't like having to
figure out how to play the

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:40.810
game that much.

00:05:40.810 --> 00:05:41.480
OK?

00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:45.960
The bet was that if that theory
is true, then what

00:05:45.960 --> 00:05:48.750
really matters, as a board game
company, is how can you

00:05:48.750 --> 00:05:51.690
get the large number of people
to play the game correctly

00:05:51.690 --> 00:05:54.780
while getting them over
that initial fear?

00:05:54.780 --> 00:05:56.560
And truth be told, what's
interesting with games like

00:05:56.560 --> 00:05:59.770
"Monopoly" is that most people
don't play the game right.

00:05:59.770 --> 00:06:02.770
And most people, when they go
and buy a box of "Monopoly,"

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:05.040
they buy it because they
remember buying it as a kid,

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:06.640
and playing it--

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:08.820
not buying it as a kid, but
playing it as a kid.

00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:11.740
And then truth be told, what
they'll do is they'll open the

00:06:11.740 --> 00:06:13.980
box, and they'll quickly browse
through the rules.

00:06:13.980 --> 00:06:16.360
And they will still play
it wrong, by the way.

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:19.650
But which is a different issue,
which is that great

00:06:19.650 --> 00:06:22.470
game designs, I think,
are very [INAUDIBLE]

00:06:22.470 --> 00:06:25.810
to errors in the way
you play that.

00:06:25.810 --> 00:06:29.460
So the interesting question then
was that if that theory

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:32.140
is true, how do you reach a lot
of the people, and teach

00:06:32.140 --> 00:06:32.700
them the game?

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:35.970
And we felt that doing digital
editions of the games would be

00:06:35.970 --> 00:06:37.290
a great way to do that.

00:06:37.290 --> 00:06:40.960
And the bet we made was that
maybe if we did digital

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:43.450
versions of our board games,
right, we could develop a

00:06:43.450 --> 00:06:47.200
virtual circle where the sales
of the physical board games

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:50.740
would drive downloads of the
digital games, and the

00:06:50.740 --> 00:06:52.960
download of the digital games
would drive the sales of the

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:53.390
board game.

00:06:53.390 --> 00:06:56.910
And you'd have that happy loop
that they develop together.

00:06:56.910 --> 00:06:58.750
So the question then becomes,
the only question that really

00:06:58.750 --> 00:07:01.010
matters as a board game company,
even though you're

00:07:01.010 --> 00:07:04.610
dealing with real cardboard
pieces like that, is how do

00:07:04.610 --> 00:07:06.920
you make sure that your digital
version is as good as

00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:07.850
your board game version?

00:07:07.850 --> 00:07:10.180
Your cardboard version?

00:07:10.180 --> 00:07:13.070
I think before we go into the
challenges about designing the

00:07:13.070 --> 00:07:15.960
digital editions of the board
games, one thing I'd like to,

00:07:15.960 --> 00:07:17.570
I'd like to do some more
differences between the

00:07:17.570 --> 00:07:19.650
digital side and the
cardboard side.

00:07:19.650 --> 00:07:22.370
So what's interesting about
the cardboard side is that

00:07:22.370 --> 00:07:26.480
it's relatively quick and
cheap to develop.

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:29.330
The typical board game today,
I'd say you can go and put a

00:07:29.330 --> 00:07:32.460
real cardboard board game in the
market for under $20,000.

00:07:32.460 --> 00:07:34.690
And you can develop that
in a couple of months.

00:07:34.690 --> 00:07:36.900
It's kind of tough to do the
same thing under the same

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:40.070
budget and the same time frame
with a digital game.

00:07:40.070 --> 00:07:43.200
So that's one thing that is in
favor of the cardboard side.

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:44.460
The other thing that is
interesting about the

00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:47.480
cardboard is that people develop
this really unique,

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:51.220
very strong, emotional
attachment to the game itself.

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:54.750
So again, taking some examples,
if you take a game

00:07:54.750 --> 00:07:58.602
box like this, even if you end
up opening this game, and not

00:07:58.602 --> 00:08:03.800
playing it for many years, and
putting it away in a corner,

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:06.350
one day you'll be just wanting
to open it again.

00:08:06.350 --> 00:08:08.840
And you're going to go, gee, I
want to clean my apartment.

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:10.740
Let's throw this, and then
you're going to keep it.

00:08:10.740 --> 00:08:13.140
And most of the time, when you
get above the trash can,

00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:14.670
you're going to say, no.

00:08:14.670 --> 00:08:15.290
Looks too good.

00:08:15.290 --> 00:08:16.220
I'm too attached to it.

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:17.740
I have good memories to it, and
you're putting it back.

00:08:17.740 --> 00:08:19.290
Or you're playing it again.

00:08:19.290 --> 00:08:19.730
OK?

00:08:19.730 --> 00:08:24.480
Whereas, if you have a digital
version, there's, I think,

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:27.150
much less of a hangup to just
pressing the Delete button.

00:08:27.150 --> 00:08:28.920
So there's a unique, emotional
attachment.

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:31.280
Now, the flip side of that,
and the bad thing on the

00:08:31.280 --> 00:08:33.500
cardboard side, as you can
imagine what happens when

00:08:33.500 --> 00:08:35.909
you're trying to ship hundreds
of thousands of these boxes

00:08:35.909 --> 00:08:37.970
across the oceans with
a small company.

00:08:37.970 --> 00:08:39.140
OK?

00:08:39.140 --> 00:08:40.130
That's kind of a pain.

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:43.549
It's definitely harder than just
publishing something on

00:08:43.549 --> 00:08:48.050
the Google Play Store
or the app store.

00:08:48.050 --> 00:08:54.350
The other thing in favor of the
digital side is the price.

00:08:54.350 --> 00:08:56.925
It tends to be a lot more
excited, and a lot more

00:08:56.925 --> 00:08:59.070
willing to talk about digital
stuff than they are about

00:08:59.070 --> 00:09:01.690
traditional card games
or board games.

00:09:01.690 --> 00:09:03.990
So that's a plus on
the digital side.

00:09:03.990 --> 00:09:05.900
And these are the main
differences that we see

00:09:05.900 --> 00:09:08.760
between the cardboard side
and the digital side.

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:10.660
Now, let's talk about game
design and where the

00:09:10.660 --> 00:09:11.760
challenges are.

00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:16.610
So the thing that is very
particular about board games

00:09:16.610 --> 00:09:18.830
as a problem for development
is that the rules you're

00:09:18.830 --> 00:09:20.970
dealing with have to
be very simple.

00:09:20.970 --> 00:09:23.730
And the reason why those rules
have to be simple is because

00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:25.570
you're playing with those
rules in your head.

00:09:25.570 --> 00:09:25.840
OK?

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:28.350
So there's a minimum of keep
you're willing to do.

00:09:28.350 --> 00:09:30.640
And if you try to do too
much, it's just not

00:09:30.640 --> 00:09:31.820
going to be much fun.

00:09:31.820 --> 00:09:34.290
And so what that means is that--
that's what I call

00:09:34.290 --> 00:09:35.360
nowhere to hide.

00:09:35.360 --> 00:09:38.490
There's no fancy graphics that
can hide a bad game.

00:09:38.490 --> 00:09:41.680
If the interaction of your rule
set with the players who

00:09:41.680 --> 00:09:46.120
are playing it is not fun,
there's no fancy graphic that

00:09:46.120 --> 00:09:46.990
is going to save you.

00:09:46.990 --> 00:09:49.440
The flip side of that is that
also means that when you

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:51.860
design a digital prototype
of the game, you can

00:09:51.860 --> 00:09:53.040
design it in text mode.

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:55.790
That's what we did with the very
first digital version of

00:09:55.790 --> 00:09:56.080
the game we had.

00:09:56.080 --> 00:09:59.060
We had a smaller card game we
launched in the company we've

00:09:59.060 --> 00:10:01.930
called "Gang of Four." And
initially, we developed a very

00:10:01.930 --> 00:10:03.910
simple text-based
version of that.

00:10:03.910 --> 00:10:07.590
And the minute we knew the thing
was going to work is

00:10:07.590 --> 00:10:09.590
when we started playing
that multi-player card

00:10:09.590 --> 00:10:11.060
game in text mode.

00:10:11.060 --> 00:10:13.680
Because that was fun, even
though it was in text mode.

00:10:13.680 --> 00:10:16.070
And so my point is, if you have
a game that is fun with

00:10:16.070 --> 00:10:18.190
sucky graphics, or in
text mode, you know

00:10:18.190 --> 00:10:20.140
you have a real winner.

00:10:20.140 --> 00:10:20.740
OK?

00:10:20.740 --> 00:10:24.350
So that's one thing that is
really important to focus on.

00:10:24.350 --> 00:10:28.550
The next thing is that board
games are fun because you're

00:10:28.550 --> 00:10:30.600
playing this simple set
of rules against

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:32.100
another human being.

00:10:32.100 --> 00:10:33.820
So yes, we can develop
artificial

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:35.220
intelligence opponents.

00:10:35.220 --> 00:10:37.930
And for some games, you can
actually develop world-class

00:10:37.930 --> 00:10:40.740
AI that will beat the
hell out of you.

00:10:40.740 --> 00:10:42.240
But that's not what is fun.

00:10:42.240 --> 00:10:44.610
What is really fun is
interacting with other people,

00:10:44.610 --> 00:10:47.470
and being able to compete mind
against mind with all the

00:10:47.470 --> 00:10:49.950
weakness and logic that
comes with that.

00:10:49.950 --> 00:10:53.040
And that creates a set of
interesting issues from a

00:10:53.040 --> 00:10:55.190
development standpoint.

00:10:55.190 --> 00:10:57.640
One of the interesting issues is
the board games tend to be

00:10:57.640 --> 00:10:58.690
turn based.

00:10:58.690 --> 00:11:00.230
So you would think, well,
they're perfect

00:11:00.230 --> 00:11:01.570
asynchronous games.

00:11:01.570 --> 00:11:03.880
Well, except when you look at
how people really play board

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:07.160
games, they aren't exactly
playing them asynchronously.

00:11:07.160 --> 00:11:08.850
I mean, yes, they are taking
their turns, but they're

00:11:08.850 --> 00:11:10.260
playing in one game session.

00:11:10.260 --> 00:11:12.900
You've don't like to
play over a billion

00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:14.130
different game sessions.

00:11:14.130 --> 00:11:17.070
And what we ended up discovering
is that what

00:11:17.070 --> 00:11:19.450
people really, really wanted
then-- and sometimes don't

00:11:19.450 --> 00:11:21.510
know how to express it-- but
what they really want with a

00:11:21.510 --> 00:11:25.760
digital board game is they want
the best of both worlds.

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:28.560
They want to be able to stop the
game asynchronously, and

00:11:28.560 --> 00:11:30.950
to start the game whatever they
want, because they might

00:11:30.950 --> 00:11:33.640
not be face to face with the
other online players.

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:36.300
But at the same time, when they
happen to be together,

00:11:36.300 --> 00:11:39.040
they want the game to perform
like a real-time game.

00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:41.590
So that's created some
difficulties.

00:11:41.590 --> 00:11:45.530
And I said the [INAUDIBLE] to
develop a basic board game

00:11:45.530 --> 00:11:47.140
that people can enjoy
as a multiplayer

00:11:47.140 --> 00:11:49.136
online games is this.

00:11:49.136 --> 00:11:52.570
It's quite significant as a
result of on those issues.

00:11:55.180 --> 00:11:58.220
So let's talk now about some
of the specific design

00:11:58.220 --> 00:12:00.260
challenges that we see.

00:12:00.260 --> 00:12:02.890
One of the challenges
is what kind of

00:12:02.890 --> 00:12:04.090
information do you display?

00:12:04.090 --> 00:12:06.530
When you have a real board game,
you don't ask yourself,

00:12:06.530 --> 00:12:07.280
what am I displaying?

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:08.860
Because if there is
a stack of cards,

00:12:08.860 --> 00:12:09.800
there's a stack of cards.

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:11.750
And everybody is looking at this
stack of cards, and gets

00:12:11.750 --> 00:12:13.210
the same information.

00:12:13.210 --> 00:12:16.860
Now, when you display that stack
of cards on the computer

00:12:16.860 --> 00:12:19.900
screen, or any electronic
device, you don't have the

00:12:19.900 --> 00:12:20.730
same resolution.

00:12:20.730 --> 00:12:23.310
You don't have the same
perception of depth that you

00:12:23.310 --> 00:12:25.270
have with the real
deck of cards.

00:12:25.270 --> 00:12:29.130
So at what point do you start
showing people that there's

00:12:29.130 --> 00:12:31.030
only a few cards left
in the deck?

00:12:31.030 --> 00:12:32.650
And how do you display
that information?

00:12:32.650 --> 00:12:34.980
Do you actually put a number
that says, there's only three

00:12:34.980 --> 00:12:36.860
cards left in the deck, Eric?

00:12:36.860 --> 00:12:40.120
Or how do you account
for that?

00:12:40.120 --> 00:12:41.630
This, I assure you,
is non-trivial.

00:12:41.630 --> 00:12:44.910
The other issue that is
non-trivial is in the real

00:12:44.910 --> 00:12:48.000
world, you can deal with
something that is quite large.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:48.270
OK?

00:12:48.270 --> 00:12:50.860
So you take a board, a
game board like this.

00:12:50.860 --> 00:12:51.070
OK?

00:12:51.070 --> 00:12:53.670
And you lay pretty, plastic
trains on them.

00:12:53.670 --> 00:12:55.280
And the information really
jumps at you.

00:12:55.280 --> 00:12:57.880
So when you're trying to
connect, let's say Vancouver

00:12:57.880 --> 00:13:01.170
to Atlanta, it's quite obvious
on the map where

00:13:01.170 --> 00:13:02.310
those things are.

00:13:02.310 --> 00:13:04.510
When you're dealing with a
screen, whether it's a tablet

00:13:04.510 --> 00:13:07.970
screen, or even worse, if you're
dealing with a smaller

00:13:07.970 --> 00:13:10.880
format screen, it's a lot
harder to see that

00:13:10.880 --> 00:13:11.710
information.

00:13:11.710 --> 00:13:14.260
And it's a lot easier
to miss some things.

00:13:14.260 --> 00:13:17.290
So you're tempted to do things
that help prompt the user, and

00:13:17.290 --> 00:13:19.830
say, OK, these are
your objectives.

00:13:19.830 --> 00:13:22.190
Well, the problem is in the
real world, you don't have

00:13:22.190 --> 00:13:23.730
something that flashes on the
board, these are your

00:13:23.730 --> 00:13:24.160
objectives.

00:13:24.160 --> 00:13:25.800
Because everybody else
would see it.

00:13:25.800 --> 00:13:26.790
Right?

00:13:26.790 --> 00:13:30.030
And again, this kind of subtle
design changes change the

00:13:30.030 --> 00:13:30.640
flavor of the game.

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:32.810
So you have to be super careful
when you implement the

00:13:32.810 --> 00:13:35.610
game, and you decide what
information to display.

00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:37.960
You have to really think through
how that's going to

00:13:37.960 --> 00:13:39.210
impact to the game.

00:13:41.620 --> 00:13:45.120
Another issue is that reality
tends to be a lot more complex

00:13:45.120 --> 00:13:46.390
than it looks.

00:13:46.390 --> 00:13:48.730
So going back to our first game,
"Gang of Four," so it's

00:13:48.730 --> 00:13:51.180
trick-taking game where
you have 64 cards.

00:13:51.180 --> 00:13:52.200
You play with four players.

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:53.270
Each players has 16 cards.

00:13:53.270 --> 00:13:55.340
And you're trying to get rid of
your cards before the other

00:13:55.340 --> 00:13:56.670
players do.

00:13:56.670 --> 00:14:00.440
And there's this thing, which
gives the game it's name,

00:14:00.440 --> 00:14:02.230
called the "Gang of Four," where
if you have four of a

00:14:02.230 --> 00:14:04.000
kind, that acts as a trump.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:07.180
And that allows you to play
on anyone's hand.

00:14:07.180 --> 00:14:09.960
And when we started programming
that game, people

00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:11.980
complained, the game
is broken.

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:13.500
There's way too many
"Gang of Fours.

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:15.150
And so, of course, if everybody
has trumps in their

00:14:15.150 --> 00:14:18.190
hands, the game kind
of breaks down.

00:14:18.190 --> 00:14:19.700
And so we looked at the
code initially.

00:14:19.700 --> 00:14:21.400
And we're thinking, OK, maybe
there's a bug somewhere.

00:14:21.400 --> 00:14:24.210
So we run some starts, and
we look at actual game

00:14:24.210 --> 00:14:25.370
plays, and so on.

00:14:25.370 --> 00:14:28.350
And the odds of having a "Gang
of Four," are exactly what

00:14:28.350 --> 00:14:29.820
that the maps say it should.

00:14:29.820 --> 00:14:31.190
So we go, wait.

00:14:31.190 --> 00:14:33.580
There is no error in the
way we programmed this.

00:14:33.580 --> 00:14:37.250
And then we realized the error
is a human error that is

00:14:37.250 --> 00:14:40.490
actually built in the physical
game itself, and that the game

00:14:40.490 --> 00:14:42.940
realized that you don't need it
to work, which is that when

00:14:42.940 --> 00:14:46.550
you play with a real deck of
cards, you will not truly do,

00:14:46.550 --> 00:14:50.110
that is, most humans won't
really, truly do a random

00:14:50.110 --> 00:14:52.580
shuffle from one end
to the next.

00:14:52.580 --> 00:14:53.100
OK?

00:14:53.100 --> 00:14:55.220
And if you do a true,
random shuffle, the

00:14:55.220 --> 00:14:56.380
game will break down.

00:14:56.380 --> 00:14:57.240
I grant you that.

00:14:57.240 --> 00:14:59.100
So if you guys play "Gang
of Four," don't

00:14:59.100 --> 00:15:01.654
shuffle it too much.

00:15:01.654 --> 00:15:03.090
OK?

00:15:03.090 --> 00:15:08.380
What that means is we had to
actually go back and program a

00:15:08.380 --> 00:15:11.420
real shuffle that kind of mimics
the way you would truly

00:15:11.420 --> 00:15:12.170
shuffle the deck.

00:15:12.170 --> 00:15:13.930
Because otherwise, the
game does break down.

00:15:13.930 --> 00:15:15.940
So that's one example.

00:15:15.940 --> 00:15:18.490
There's another even more
embarrassing and simple

00:15:18.490 --> 00:15:22.390
example of reality being more
complex than it looks, or

00:15:22.390 --> 00:15:24.790
deeper and richer than it
looks, which is almost

00:15:24.790 --> 00:15:28.230
embarrassing to admit, which is
linked to another game we

00:15:28.230 --> 00:15:30.560
have called "Small World." And
in "Small World," it's kind of

00:15:30.560 --> 00:15:33.280
like a fantasy game of "Risk."
and you have a die.

00:15:33.280 --> 00:15:35.800
And that die you can roll on
your last conquest to try to

00:15:35.800 --> 00:15:37.170
grab your territory.

00:15:37.170 --> 00:15:39.640
And that die has a feature that
is a bit unique, which is

00:15:39.640 --> 00:15:43.070
that there's one side with one
pip, one with two, one with

00:15:43.070 --> 00:15:47.660
three, and the other three
sides happen to be blank.

00:15:47.660 --> 00:15:48.320
OK.

00:15:48.320 --> 00:15:48.830
No big deal.

00:15:48.830 --> 00:15:51.100
When you play with the real
game, you grab the die.

00:15:51.100 --> 00:15:52.770
It seemed to really
jump at you.

00:15:52.770 --> 00:15:54.040
I don't need to write
anything in the

00:15:54.040 --> 00:15:55.590
rules that says, beware.

00:15:55.590 --> 00:15:58.160
This dice has three
blank sides.

00:15:58.160 --> 00:15:58.770
OK?

00:15:58.770 --> 00:16:01.760
Well, when we programmed the
electronic version, we started

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:03.330
getting lots of reviews.

00:16:03.330 --> 00:16:04.960
And on the upside, it's very
frustrating because you can't

00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:07.850
leave feedback or answers to
these people on their reviews.

00:16:07.850 --> 00:16:09.880
They're saying, the
game is cheating.

00:16:09.880 --> 00:16:11.850
I'm always rolling blanks.

00:16:11.850 --> 00:16:13.390
I'd realize, well, yeah.

00:16:13.390 --> 00:16:14.930
it's rolling the die for you.

00:16:14.930 --> 00:16:17.220
And when it's rolling on the
screen, you don't really ever

00:16:17.220 --> 00:16:20.610
get a chance to see it's
literally side by side.

00:16:20.610 --> 00:16:21.580
It kind of rolls too fast.

00:16:21.580 --> 00:16:23.940
It rolls like a real die, and
you can't really know that

00:16:23.940 --> 00:16:25.250
there's three blank sides.

00:16:25.250 --> 00:16:27.540
So that's another example where
you really need to be

00:16:27.540 --> 00:16:34.430
careful about how you handle
the display of information,

00:16:34.430 --> 00:16:38.710
and how you translate the
physical components into the

00:16:38.710 --> 00:16:40.680
digital site.

00:16:40.680 --> 00:16:43.890
One of the challenges is
the perception of time.

00:16:43.890 --> 00:16:46.050
When you're playing face
to face, you have the

00:16:46.050 --> 00:16:46.800
interaction.

00:16:46.800 --> 00:16:48.300
And that's true by the way--

00:16:48.300 --> 00:16:50.500
it's not so much a digital
versus cardboard issue here.

00:16:50.500 --> 00:16:54.270
It's an issue of playing face
to face verus playing online

00:16:54.270 --> 00:16:58.640
against people that are on
the remote connection.

00:16:58.640 --> 00:17:01.160
Which is that when you are
playing face to face, there is

00:17:01.160 --> 00:17:04.319
so many human interactions that
doesn't really pertain to

00:17:04.319 --> 00:17:07.170
the game itself, that comes
into play, that your

00:17:07.170 --> 00:17:09.700
perception of time is vastly
different from what it is when

00:17:09.700 --> 00:17:12.313
you just focus, looking
on your screen.

00:17:12.313 --> 00:17:12.790
OK?

00:17:12.790 --> 00:17:15.200
And what that means is in a game
like "Gang of Four" where

00:17:15.200 --> 00:17:17.180
you can play a hand or you
can pass, even if you

00:17:17.180 --> 00:17:18.200
could play that hand.

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:20.569
And that information is crucial,
because it's giving

00:17:20.569 --> 00:17:22.700
me, as your opponent, a
lot of information.

00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:26.000
If I see that you hesitate
about passing, I know

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:29.100
something about your hand that
you don't want me to know.

00:17:29.100 --> 00:17:30.680
And what's happening is when
you're just watching the

00:17:30.680 --> 00:17:32.620
screen, you have no
one to look at.

00:17:32.620 --> 00:17:35.370
So you're missing that whole,
additional information, social

00:17:35.370 --> 00:17:36.290
information.

00:17:36.290 --> 00:17:37.760
And as a result of that--

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:39.090
and we did this, really
timed it.

00:17:39.090 --> 00:17:40.110
We did the test--

00:17:40.110 --> 00:17:42.350
If you pause for even
less than a half a

00:17:42.350 --> 00:17:44.800
second, we will notice.

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:46.720
Or the good players
will notice.

00:17:46.720 --> 00:17:47.140
OK?

00:17:47.140 --> 00:17:48.380
And that's something
they would never

00:17:48.380 --> 00:17:49.720
notice in the real world.

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:50.190
OK?

00:17:50.190 --> 00:17:54.420
So that is a challenge, and that
means that people will

00:17:54.420 --> 00:17:55.350
play the game differently.

00:17:55.350 --> 00:17:57.700
And you have to accept that
there's some things you just

00:17:57.700 --> 00:18:00.070
won't to be able to change, and
people will play the game

00:18:00.070 --> 00:18:01.860
differently.

00:18:01.860 --> 00:18:04.850
Another example of that is
because you have no one to

00:18:04.850 --> 00:18:08.140
look at, and interact with
directly, you will focus on

00:18:08.140 --> 00:18:09.680
what information you're
presented with.

00:18:09.680 --> 00:18:11.870
So again, looking at that very
simple card game, "Gang of

00:18:11.870 --> 00:18:14.220
Four," it's a game where there's
four players, but

00:18:14.220 --> 00:18:15.390
there's only one winner.

00:18:15.390 --> 00:18:17.490
And there's no second,
third, fourth player.

00:18:17.490 --> 00:18:20.190
You're either the winner,
or you lost.

00:18:20.190 --> 00:18:23.700
And when you play the game
online, all you get to see at

00:18:23.700 --> 00:18:26.620
is potentially an avatar, the
name of that avatar, which we

00:18:26.620 --> 00:18:27.870
usually don't change
during the game

00:18:27.870 --> 00:18:29.550
itself, and the score.

00:18:29.550 --> 00:18:32.620
And as a result of that, you
focus on the score a lot more

00:18:32.620 --> 00:18:33.920
than you would in
the real world.

00:18:33.920 --> 00:18:36.520
In the real world, people would
write everyone's names.

00:18:36.520 --> 00:18:38.190
They would write down
the scores.

00:18:38.190 --> 00:18:40.650
And at the end of every couple
of hands, people will go and

00:18:40.650 --> 00:18:42.600
say, OK, what is your score?

00:18:42.600 --> 00:18:44.190
What is your score?

00:18:44.190 --> 00:18:46.035
And that's kind of in the
background of your mind, in

00:18:46.035 --> 00:18:46.710
the back of your mind.

00:18:46.710 --> 00:18:49.140
But it's not something that
is facing you on the

00:18:49.140 --> 00:18:50.140
screen all the time.

00:18:50.140 --> 00:18:52.080
And as a result of that, what
we've seen is competitive

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:56.980
players who play online get into
this metagame where the

00:18:56.980 --> 00:18:59.390
scoring information of all the
partners is so present in

00:18:59.390 --> 00:19:01.450
their mind that whole time that
it alters the way they

00:19:01.450 --> 00:19:06.440
play the game, and the
strategies they use.

00:19:06.440 --> 00:19:11.060
Another unique challenge for the
digital versions is that

00:19:11.060 --> 00:19:12.580
people will have a hard
time believing

00:19:12.580 --> 00:19:14.746
that AI doesn't cheat.

00:19:14.746 --> 00:19:15.170
OK?

00:19:15.170 --> 00:19:17.480
A really hard time.

00:19:17.480 --> 00:19:18.310
So we have a game.

00:19:18.310 --> 00:19:19.420
It's a World War II game.

00:19:19.420 --> 00:19:20.390
It's called "Memoir 44."

00:19:20.390 --> 00:19:23.220
And it's a game where you
get to roll lots of die.

00:19:23.220 --> 00:19:30.760
And when you roll those dices,
people are not willing to

00:19:30.760 --> 00:19:34.980
believe that the computer rolls
the same dice you are.

00:19:34.980 --> 00:19:37.290
So people ask us, they'll
say, I'm a programmer.

00:19:37.290 --> 00:19:38.660
I want to see your routine.

00:19:38.660 --> 00:19:40.200
So we show the actual code.

00:19:40.200 --> 00:19:42.020
And then they say, I want
to see recalls.

00:19:42.020 --> 00:19:44.690
So we published 500,000
game recalls.

00:19:44.690 --> 00:19:47.160
And we explained to those
people, oh, by the way, the

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:50.850
dice-rolling function has
no idea who it give that

00:19:50.850 --> 00:19:51.660
information to.

00:19:51.660 --> 00:19:55.330
So the dice-rolling function is
exactly the same as rolling

00:19:55.330 --> 00:19:56.740
the computer dice,
and your dice.

00:19:56.740 --> 00:19:58.550
It doesn't know when it's
giving the results.

00:19:58.550 --> 00:20:00.330
People still don't believe it.

00:20:00.330 --> 00:20:02.930
The reason why people don't
believe it is very simple.

00:20:02.930 --> 00:20:04.750
It's a game that you
play on the board.

00:20:04.750 --> 00:20:07.940
And we have the position of
different pieces, and so on.

00:20:07.940 --> 00:20:10.110
That's going to be of impact
on the strategy.

00:20:10.110 --> 00:20:12.410
And that's something that is
kind of expensive to compute,

00:20:12.410 --> 00:20:15.110
and in some instances, actually
tough to compute on

00:20:15.110 --> 00:20:16.730
the computer.

00:20:16.730 --> 00:20:19.090
The flip side of that is with
the computer, what you can

00:20:19.090 --> 00:20:23.590
really do much better than 99.9%
of the human population

00:20:23.590 --> 00:20:25.320
is you can compute the odds.

00:20:25.320 --> 00:20:26.790
And you can compute the
odds very well.

00:20:26.790 --> 00:20:29.460
So I'm holding a dice, and I'm
looking for this sample, and

00:20:29.460 --> 00:20:30.920
that sample, but not that one.

00:20:30.920 --> 00:20:33.160
This is five, and I'm looking
for that one and that one.

00:20:33.160 --> 00:20:36.050
The computer will do much better
than the typical human.

00:20:36.050 --> 00:20:38.530
So as with all of that, when you
program AI, we say, well,

00:20:38.530 --> 00:20:40.420
let's use the computer
strength, and let's

00:20:40.420 --> 00:20:41.070
program it that way.

00:20:41.070 --> 00:20:45.560
So our AI got really good at
maximizing its dice rolls.

00:20:45.560 --> 00:20:47.630
And that, combined with the fact
that the perception of

00:20:47.630 --> 00:20:49.510
time changes, and that when
you're playing in the

00:20:49.510 --> 00:20:53.510
computer, you see the dice rolls
happen in a shorter, a

00:20:53.510 --> 00:20:55.252
compressed period of time.

00:20:55.252 --> 00:20:57.050
Totally changes your
perception.

00:20:57.050 --> 00:20:57.530
OK?

00:20:57.530 --> 00:20:58.510
And it's really rigged up.

00:20:58.510 --> 00:21:00.610
I mean, you can show people
the actual evidence.

00:21:00.610 --> 00:21:03.080
It's basically we've come to the
conclusion it's impossible

00:21:03.080 --> 00:21:06.630
to convince people the
AI isn't cheating.

00:21:06.630 --> 00:21:07.320
OK?

00:21:07.320 --> 00:21:12.160
The other interesting challenge
with AIs is that

00:21:12.160 --> 00:21:15.730
sometimes the AI, the game
looks simple to play.

00:21:15.730 --> 00:21:17.740
The rules are simple, like
"Ticket to Ride." So you

00:21:17.740 --> 00:21:20.600
think, well, the AI should
be easy to program.

00:21:20.600 --> 00:21:21.960
Well, not so.

00:21:21.960 --> 00:21:23.260
It can be very difficult.

00:21:23.260 --> 00:21:24.730
It can be like really
difficult.

00:21:24.730 --> 00:21:26.670
And the flip side of that is
there's games that look

00:21:26.670 --> 00:21:29.480
complex to play for humans, and
the AI is actually quite

00:21:29.480 --> 00:21:32.120
simple to program.

00:21:32.120 --> 00:21:35.700
One thing that we like to do
is we don't think it's that

00:21:35.700 --> 00:21:36.970
interesting to try
to develop--

00:21:36.970 --> 00:21:39.070
it's challenging, and it's not
that interesting, usually, to

00:21:39.070 --> 00:21:43.190
try to develop an AI that
plays like a human does.

00:21:43.190 --> 00:21:45.480
Because in that case, just
go and find a friend.

00:21:45.480 --> 00:21:46.010
I mean, come on.

00:21:46.010 --> 00:21:47.190
It's not that difficult,
especially if

00:21:47.190 --> 00:21:49.010
you can play online.

00:21:49.010 --> 00:21:50.630
So we tried to take
advantage of that.

00:21:50.630 --> 00:21:53.620
So with a game like "Small
World," for instance, we use

00:21:53.620 --> 00:21:56.230
the fact that the initial
version of the game was only a

00:21:56.230 --> 00:21:57.090
two-player game.

00:21:57.090 --> 00:21:59.330
And in the two-player game,
it's a zero-sum game.

00:21:59.330 --> 00:22:01.740
So whatever points I'm scoring,
I'm taking away from

00:22:01.740 --> 00:22:03.160
you, and vice versa.

00:22:03.160 --> 00:22:05.680
And as a result of that, we
used that in the way we

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:06.310
designed the AI.

00:22:06.310 --> 00:22:10.195
And people felt that the game
was super aggressive.

00:22:10.195 --> 00:22:13.540
It was super aggressive because
you'd put at a stack

00:22:13.540 --> 00:22:16.250
of armies like that
on one territory.

00:22:16.250 --> 00:22:18.690
And in the regular play in the
real world, people will never

00:22:18.690 --> 00:22:19.900
go after that stack.

00:22:19.900 --> 00:22:23.100
They're literally physically
intimidated by the height of

00:22:23.100 --> 00:22:23.870
your stack.

00:22:23.870 --> 00:22:26.990
Even though all you need is
one more token, OK, and it

00:22:26.990 --> 00:22:28.980
doesn't matter whether the stack
is that high, or that

00:22:28.980 --> 00:22:31.060
high from a score standpoint.

00:22:31.060 --> 00:22:33.760
And so we were able to develop
something that played really

00:22:33.760 --> 00:22:34.920
fundamentally different.

00:22:34.920 --> 00:22:37.410
And that's kind of fun, because
what that shows you is

00:22:37.410 --> 00:22:40.310
that when you're developing
digital games the right way,

00:22:40.310 --> 00:22:44.040
they will allow you to learn
the game, but they will

00:22:44.040 --> 00:22:45.650
scratch a different itch.

00:22:45.650 --> 00:22:49.640
So what you get as a player
from playing the digital

00:22:49.640 --> 00:22:51.490
version of the game
will be different.

00:22:51.490 --> 00:22:53.830
And the pleasure you'll get out
of it, and the frustration

00:22:53.830 --> 00:22:55.570
you'll get out of it sometimes,
too, will be

00:22:55.570 --> 00:22:57.980
different from the one when
you playing the cardboard.

00:22:57.980 --> 00:23:01.860
And that really has made the
game a success, the business a

00:23:01.860 --> 00:23:04.730
success, because then you really
do get that feedback

00:23:04.730 --> 00:23:08.250
loop where people who play the
physical board games are aware

00:23:08.250 --> 00:23:09.460
of the game, and are interested

00:23:09.460 --> 00:23:10.590
in playing it online.

00:23:10.590 --> 00:23:13.860
And that creates a base level,
if you want, of sales online.

00:23:13.860 --> 00:23:16.340
That allows you to be visible
and stay visible if you have a

00:23:16.340 --> 00:23:18.350
large number of physical
players out there.

00:23:18.350 --> 00:23:20.990
And in turn, because you're
visible in the charts, people

00:23:20.990 --> 00:23:22.330
can buy the online version.

00:23:22.330 --> 00:23:24.870
Some people will discover the
game online, and eventually

00:23:24.870 --> 00:23:27.300
they'll want to go and buy
the physical board game.

00:23:27.300 --> 00:23:28.920
Because the physical board
game will give

00:23:28.920 --> 00:23:30.730
them different things.

00:23:30.730 --> 00:23:32.460
And one of the things that
will be different is the

00:23:32.460 --> 00:23:34.930
memories that you
get out of it.

00:23:34.930 --> 00:23:37.960
If you think about when you
were playing board games,

00:23:37.960 --> 00:23:40.330
maybe as a child, I'm sure
most of you can jog some

00:23:40.330 --> 00:23:42.440
memories of some specific
games where you remember

00:23:42.440 --> 00:23:43.860
So-And-So did that after
he was going to

00:23:43.860 --> 00:23:45.390
capture that territory.

00:23:45.390 --> 00:23:46.110
And it's much harder--

00:23:46.110 --> 00:23:47.280
I'm not saying it's
impossible--

00:23:47.280 --> 00:23:50.230
but it's much harder to have the
same emotional connection

00:23:50.230 --> 00:23:51.270
with a digital site.

00:23:51.270 --> 00:23:55.070
So being able to play on both
fronts is really something

00:23:55.070 --> 00:23:57.510
that we strive to do.

00:23:57.510 --> 00:24:01.450
And that's really, I think, that
really captures what we

00:24:01.450 --> 00:24:02.860
try to do as a business.

00:24:02.860 --> 00:24:06.625
We really enjoy being one foot
on the physical side, one foot

00:24:06.625 --> 00:24:08.790
on the digital side.

00:24:08.790 --> 00:24:10.950
That allows us to keep the
business interesting because,

00:24:10.950 --> 00:24:14.740
frankly, the cardboard side,
it's interesting initially

00:24:14.740 --> 00:24:17.100
because the spectrum of time is
so different and it impacts

00:24:17.100 --> 00:24:19.000
the way you drive and you
develop your business.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:20.990
But after a while, you've
figured it out.

00:24:20.990 --> 00:24:21.210
OK?

00:24:21.210 --> 00:24:23.700
So you understand how that
fragmented, antiquated

00:24:23.700 --> 00:24:25.310
distribution network works.

00:24:25.310 --> 00:24:27.090
And it kind of gets boring.

00:24:27.090 --> 00:24:29.100
The nice thing on the digital
side is things change so

00:24:29.100 --> 00:24:30.740
quickly that you always have
to stay on your toes.

00:24:30.740 --> 00:24:35.280
And so being able to combine
the two really makes for a

00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:37.570
fun, lifestyle business.

00:24:37.570 --> 00:24:40.170
And I think that kind of sums
up what I wanted to discuss

00:24:40.170 --> 00:24:43.180
about for getting the
design of the games.

00:24:43.180 --> 00:24:46.482
And I'd be happy to open
it to Q&amp;A now.

00:24:46.482 --> 00:24:51.350
