00:25:00.100 --> 00:25:02.750
AUDIENCE: The digital versions
of your games are so good.

00:25:02.750 --> 00:25:05.220
I was just wondering how you
guys made that pivot, or how

00:25:05.220 --> 00:25:08.116
you built up the team to
start creating those.

00:25:08.116 --> 00:25:10.320
ERIC HAUTEMONT: So I think
there's a couple of things

00:25:10.320 --> 00:25:12.286
that gave us an edge.

00:25:12.286 --> 00:25:17.010
One is that-- and that goes back
to the fact that people

00:25:17.010 --> 00:25:20.240
in the cardboard business
will fail in a hurry.

00:25:20.240 --> 00:25:22.630
That's one of the things that,
for us, makes it interesting,

00:25:22.630 --> 00:25:24.720
which is that there is
no shortcut, and

00:25:24.720 --> 00:25:25.950
you need to go slow.

00:25:25.950 --> 00:25:29.420
And we tried to adopt the same
thing with the digital side.

00:25:29.420 --> 00:25:31.900
So one of the nice things about
the board game side is

00:25:31.900 --> 00:25:32.730
once you have--

00:25:32.730 --> 00:25:34.790
It's both the best and the worst
business in the world,

00:25:34.790 --> 00:25:37.040
because it's like the book
publishing business.

00:25:37.040 --> 00:25:39.820
Until you have a hit, it's
a really, really bad

00:25:39.820 --> 00:25:40.630
business to be in.

00:25:40.630 --> 00:25:43.460
And I would recommend to no one
interested in making money

00:25:43.460 --> 00:25:45.300
to go in the board
game business.

00:25:45.300 --> 00:25:45.860
OK?

00:25:45.860 --> 00:25:48.080
Because it's expensive
to manufacture.

00:25:48.080 --> 00:25:49.360
It's expensive to distribute.

00:25:49.360 --> 00:25:50.800
And it's low margins.

00:25:50.800 --> 00:25:51.300
OK?

00:25:51.300 --> 00:25:53.800
But that's only true until
you get a hit.

00:25:53.800 --> 00:25:56.870
And the day you get the next
"Ticket to Ride," or the next

00:25:56.870 --> 00:25:59.690
"Harry Potter" in the book
business, that becomes a

00:25:59.690 --> 00:26:00.590
wonderful business.

00:26:00.590 --> 00:26:03.170
Because once a year, you
call your printer.

00:26:03.170 --> 00:26:05.350
You say, please, pretty
please, print

00:26:05.350 --> 00:26:07.750
me some more money.

00:26:07.750 --> 00:26:09.460
There's very little
competition,

00:26:09.460 --> 00:26:10.610
and it lasts forever.

00:26:10.610 --> 00:26:11.200
And it's true.

00:26:11.200 --> 00:26:12.980
I mean, we look at "Ticket to
Ride." So we came up with

00:26:12.980 --> 00:26:15.230
"Ticket to Ride" 10 years ago,
and we've been selling more

00:26:15.230 --> 00:26:18.520
"Ticket to Ride" every single
year of the board game.

00:26:18.520 --> 00:26:20.520
Every single year than
the year before.

00:26:20.520 --> 00:26:24.620
And our marketing expenses
are literally this much.

00:26:24.620 --> 00:26:26.970
As my partner and friend, Mark,
likes to say, all the

00:26:26.970 --> 00:26:28.120
marketing is in the game box.

00:26:28.120 --> 00:26:31.360
We put all the money in the box,
and the word of mouth is

00:26:31.360 --> 00:26:32.090
what's going to do it.

00:26:32.090 --> 00:26:33.550
Now, the flip side of that
is the word of mouth

00:26:33.550 --> 00:26:36.170
only goes so fast.

00:26:36.170 --> 00:26:39.860
So if you're in a hurry, just
spend money and waste it.

00:26:39.860 --> 00:26:43.470
So I think the luxury of having
those hits under our

00:26:43.470 --> 00:26:47.200
belt on the cardboard side has
allowed us to go very slow on

00:26:47.200 --> 00:26:48.190
the digital side.

00:26:48.190 --> 00:26:48.450
OK?

00:26:48.450 --> 00:26:50.630
So the first version of "Ticket
to Ride," the digital

00:26:50.630 --> 00:26:54.320
board game, was actually on
the web back in 2005 as a

00:26:54.320 --> 00:26:55.610
small Java app.

00:26:55.610 --> 00:26:57.370
And initially, it was free.

00:26:57.370 --> 00:27:00.060
And what we realized, as people
started playing it, is

00:27:00.060 --> 00:27:02.590
that some people were
playing it a lot.

00:27:02.590 --> 00:27:04.100
I mean a whole lot.

00:27:04.100 --> 00:27:05.450
Like there's some people--

00:27:05.450 --> 00:27:07.530
I won't name names-- but there's
some people that have

00:27:07.530 --> 00:27:09.450
played in excess of
80,000 games of

00:27:09.450 --> 00:27:11.340
"Ticket to Ride" online.

00:27:11.340 --> 00:27:14.460
Now, online plays faster than
the real board game, so if

00:27:14.460 --> 00:27:15.950
you're really fast and good--

00:27:15.950 --> 00:27:18.530
and by the time you're at your
80,000th game, you should be

00:27:18.530 --> 00:27:21.560
fast, at least, if not good--

00:27:21.560 --> 00:27:24.180
you'd be able to play maybe
three to five minutes, if it's

00:27:24.180 --> 00:27:25.040
a two-player game.

00:27:25.040 --> 00:27:26.380
But then they do do the math.

00:27:26.380 --> 00:27:28.920
80,000 times three to five
minutes, that's a pretty good

00:27:28.920 --> 00:27:30.430
chunk of time.

00:27:30.430 --> 00:27:32.585
So we realized that maybe
there was a business for

00:27:32.585 --> 00:27:34.500
actually selling the
digital versions.

00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:38.450
And what really, I think,
allowed us to get to the next

00:27:38.450 --> 00:27:41.880
level was the unveiling
of the iPad.

00:27:41.880 --> 00:27:44.400
And we have the iPad,
and all the tablets.

00:27:44.400 --> 00:27:45.380
It's not specific to the iPad.

00:27:45.380 --> 00:27:49.340
But where I think the tablets,
and not the phones, but the

00:27:49.340 --> 00:27:52.570
tablets differ from every other
form of device is that

00:27:52.570 --> 00:27:55.190
they have this first device that
I think are really-- or

00:27:55.190 --> 00:27:58.390
can in certain usage be very
transparent, meaning that you

00:27:58.390 --> 00:28:02.440
can play on that device, and you
don't realize consciously

00:28:02.440 --> 00:28:03.690
on that, that you're
sitting in front of

00:28:03.690 --> 00:28:04.360
an electronic device.

00:28:04.360 --> 00:28:06.350
When I'm sitting in front of
computer playing a game of

00:28:06.350 --> 00:28:09.220
"Ticket to Ride," I know I'm
intimately aware that I'm in

00:28:09.220 --> 00:28:12.180
front of my computer playing
"Ticket to Ride." When you are

00:28:12.180 --> 00:28:14.070
playing on the tablet, sometimes
you can forget that.

00:28:14.070 --> 00:28:17.590
And it's especially true when
you're playing face to face on

00:28:17.590 --> 00:28:18.460
the tablet.

00:28:18.460 --> 00:28:21.750
So the answer--

00:28:21.750 --> 00:28:23.710
I guess the long-winded winded
answer to your question is the

00:28:23.710 --> 00:28:26.380
reason we've been successful, I
think, is we take our time.

00:28:26.380 --> 00:28:27.800
We don't hesitate to be late.

00:28:27.800 --> 00:28:30.040
So we have lots of people that
come to us, and they say, we

00:28:30.040 --> 00:28:31.020
have a new platform.

00:28:31.020 --> 00:28:31.970
You must do that.

00:28:31.970 --> 00:28:34.950
So a couple of years ago, we had
people say, oh, if you're

00:28:34.950 --> 00:28:36.620
not on Social Live, if
you're not on social

00:28:36.620 --> 00:28:38.760
networks, you're dead.

00:28:38.760 --> 00:28:40.440
And we're like, maybe
we're dead.

00:28:40.440 --> 00:28:41.510
Maybe we're not.

00:28:41.510 --> 00:28:44.160
The nice thing is we
can afford to wait.

00:28:44.160 --> 00:28:46.170
And the same thing was true with
consoles, where people

00:28:46.170 --> 00:28:48.500
come in and say, you need
to be on this console.

00:28:48.500 --> 00:28:50.620
Well, no, we don't really,
actually, because we're doing

00:28:50.620 --> 00:28:51.780
just fine on the
cardboard side.

00:28:51.780 --> 00:28:53.520
We've got the digital side
of the business.

00:28:53.520 --> 00:28:55.980
And so if we're not on that
version, we can be on the next

00:28:55.980 --> 00:28:57.330
version, or the next version.

00:28:57.330 --> 00:28:59.650
And by the way, if we miss the
train, maybe that train will

00:28:59.650 --> 00:29:00.370
go off road somewhere.

00:29:00.370 --> 00:29:01.700
And we don't have to
worry about it.

00:29:01.700 --> 00:29:04.538
And we still have some time.

00:29:04.538 --> 00:29:06.160
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:29:06.160 --> 00:29:08.940
So I play "Memorial 44," and
after your comments about the

00:29:08.940 --> 00:29:12.140
AI, I was wondering if you've
ever felt the urge to actually

00:29:12.140 --> 00:29:15.420
tweak the AI so that
it cheats, but in

00:29:15.420 --> 00:29:17.200
favor of the player.

00:29:17.200 --> 00:29:18.290
A lot of video games do that.

00:29:18.290 --> 00:29:20.340
Like they make it seem like it's
fair, but it's actually

00:29:20.340 --> 00:29:23.070
in favor of the player, so the
player doesn't complain.

00:29:23.070 --> 00:29:25.540
ERIC HAUTEMONT: No, we don't
for a couple of reasons.

00:29:25.540 --> 00:29:30.690
One is an economical reason,
which is that we're a very

00:29:30.690 --> 00:29:32.030
small company, actually,
in terms of people.

00:29:32.030 --> 00:29:34.830
We are 16 people worldwide, and
that includes the people

00:29:34.830 --> 00:29:37.420
that do the physical cardboard
stuff, and all the people who

00:29:37.420 --> 00:29:40.510
do the programming and the art
for the online versions.

00:29:40.510 --> 00:29:43.690
So once we have a version that
we're happy with, we try not

00:29:43.690 --> 00:29:46.680
to tinker with it too much
because it's expensive.

00:29:46.680 --> 00:29:48.180
It's expensive not in
terms of money.

00:29:48.180 --> 00:29:50.130
It's expensive in terms
of our time.

00:29:50.130 --> 00:29:53.030
And whatever time we spend
developing these additional

00:29:53.030 --> 00:29:55.970
tweaks to the AI is time that we
don't spend taking the next

00:29:55.970 --> 00:29:57.000
game online.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:59.620
So that's one reason.

00:29:59.620 --> 00:30:02.090
The other one is that we
actually think that part of

00:30:02.090 --> 00:30:05.760
the fun of doing AIs, or of
playing the AIs, is figuring

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:06.600
out the AI.

00:30:06.600 --> 00:30:08.280
It's almost like a puzzle.

00:30:08.280 --> 00:30:11.820
And once you've solved that
puzzle, than frankly, we want

00:30:11.820 --> 00:30:13.750
to encourage people to
go and play online.

00:30:13.750 --> 00:30:17.130
There's no way-- we could have
the entire company work on AIs

00:30:17.130 --> 00:30:20.510
for "Memorial 44" for the next
10 years, and I still don't

00:30:20.510 --> 00:30:23.510
think we could duplicate the
variety of opponents that are

00:30:23.510 --> 00:30:26.130
playing face to face.

00:30:26.130 --> 00:30:28.240
