00:32:17.781 --> 00:32:20.630
AUDIENCE: So my daughter and I
would like to play "Ticket to

00:32:20.630 --> 00:32:24.570
Ride," but I find when we play
together-- she's eight--

00:32:24.570 --> 00:32:26.475
we don't play the sort of
cutthroat game of like, oh,

00:32:26.475 --> 00:32:27.370
I'm going to cut you off.

00:32:27.370 --> 00:32:28.720
And you can't finish a route.

00:32:28.720 --> 00:32:31.710
But we kind of played in a
cooperative way, where oh, I

00:32:31.710 --> 00:32:32.790
see you're trying to
build over here.

00:32:32.790 --> 00:32:33.925
I'll build over there.

00:32:33.925 --> 00:32:36.060
Have you thought about what some
of your games, thinking

00:32:36.060 --> 00:32:39.420
about ways you could make them
like cooperative variants of

00:32:39.420 --> 00:32:41.290
the games, or cooperative
gameplay, so that for

00:32:41.290 --> 00:32:42.190
families and stuff?

00:32:42.190 --> 00:32:42.875
Those kind of environments?

00:32:42.875 --> 00:32:43.370
ERIC HAUTEMONT: Yeah.

00:32:43.370 --> 00:32:46.860
So we actually have a game
called "Shadows Over Camelot,"

00:32:46.860 --> 00:32:48.820
which is a game that is actually
built around the

00:32:48.820 --> 00:32:51.280
whole idea of being cooperative,
meaning that all

00:32:51.280 --> 00:32:52.900
the players together
play against the

00:32:52.900 --> 00:32:54.630
game mechanics itself.

00:32:54.630 --> 00:32:56.710
Now, even there, I'm
afraid though, we

00:32:56.710 --> 00:32:57.620
couldn't quite help it.

00:32:57.620 --> 00:33:01.250
So we did put a small wrinkle
in that, which is that even

00:33:01.250 --> 00:33:03.170
though all the players are
playing together against the

00:33:03.170 --> 00:33:06.280
game mechanic itself, there is
always the possibility, or the

00:33:06.280 --> 00:33:09.080
risk, even in your case, that
one of the players is a

00:33:09.080 --> 00:33:14.183
traitor, and will win if
everybody else loses.

00:33:14.183 --> 00:33:14.870
OK?

00:33:14.870 --> 00:33:17.020
But you don't have a guarantee
that that player is there.

00:33:17.020 --> 00:33:19.760
And if you want to play it in
purely cooperative mode, you

00:33:19.760 --> 00:33:21.840
can do that.

00:33:21.840 --> 00:33:24.610
On a game like "Ticket to Ride,"
there's a way to play

00:33:24.610 --> 00:33:27.040
cooperatively, like on the
Asia map, for instance.

00:33:27.040 --> 00:33:28.300
We have a team version.

00:33:28.300 --> 00:33:31.160
So where players have a limited
amount of information,

00:33:31.160 --> 00:33:33.350
the connections, how they
can share together.

00:33:33.350 --> 00:33:35.300
So you're playing cooperatively,
but you still

00:33:35.300 --> 00:33:37.790
playing competitively against
other players.

00:33:37.790 --> 00:33:42.490
And the reason for that is,
again, with real board games,

00:33:42.490 --> 00:33:44.670
you must use a very simple
set up rules.

00:33:44.670 --> 00:33:47.250
Otherwise, you lose the vast
majority of players.

00:33:47.250 --> 00:33:50.230
And so it's difficult to keep
the tension that makes a game

00:33:50.230 --> 00:33:53.030
fun and tight when being
purely cooperatively.

00:33:53.030 --> 00:33:56.530
so unless you design the game
from the ground up for that, I

00:33:56.530 --> 00:33:58.580
think it's very difficult to
take a game that is not a

00:33:58.580 --> 00:34:02.230
cooperative game and
turn it into one.

00:34:04.810 --> 00:34:07.120
AUDIENCE: I was wondering if
you could speak a bit about

00:34:07.120 --> 00:34:09.909
the collaboration process
between the company and

00:34:09.909 --> 00:34:13.270
working designers, and sort
of like where the work--

00:34:13.270 --> 00:34:14.760
how the work is split up.

00:34:14.760 --> 00:34:18.139
And also, I'm also curious about
sort of like the origins

00:34:18.139 --> 00:34:20.210
of "Ticket to Ride," and
how you got started

00:34:20.210 --> 00:34:21.480
creating the game.

00:34:21.480 --> 00:34:21.770
ERIC HAUTEMONT: Sure.

00:34:21.770 --> 00:34:22.310
OK.

00:34:22.310 --> 00:34:24.370
So we're getting at how we
work with game designers.

00:34:24.370 --> 00:34:29.560
It really runs the whole gamut
for a number of reasons, one

00:34:29.560 --> 00:34:34.254
of which is that we haven't met
two game designers that

00:34:34.254 --> 00:34:35.090
are the same.

00:34:35.090 --> 00:34:37.100
There's actually very few people
in the business who

00:34:37.100 --> 00:34:41.360
make a living, full time,
from game design.

00:34:41.360 --> 00:34:43.750
Most of those that do make
a living full time tend

00:34:43.750 --> 00:34:44.860
to be in the US.

00:34:44.860 --> 00:34:47.360
But there's game designers
all around the world.

00:34:47.360 --> 00:34:49.969
And we've seen people that have
submitted prototypes to

00:34:49.969 --> 00:34:51.909
us that we're working for the
Secret Service, that we're

00:34:51.909 --> 00:34:55.780
working for that Coast Guard, on
the equivalent of the Coast

00:34:55.780 --> 00:34:58.120
Guards in other countries.

00:34:58.120 --> 00:34:59.430
People that are teachers.

00:34:59.430 --> 00:35:00.510
People that are priests.

00:35:00.510 --> 00:35:02.740
All kind of people.

00:35:02.740 --> 00:35:05.460
And so depending on the work
they do, and the type of

00:35:05.460 --> 00:35:08.140
designed they do, the amount
of interactions we have is

00:35:08.140 --> 00:35:10.450
more or less significant.

00:35:10.450 --> 00:35:12.090
So we have some people that have
worked with us, and they

00:35:12.090 --> 00:35:14.890
say, I have a design,
and the design was

00:35:14.890 --> 00:35:17.030
perfect from the get-go.

00:35:17.030 --> 00:35:21.020
And so the interaction we had
with them was sending a

00:35:21.020 --> 00:35:24.190
publishing agreement, and then
keeping them informed as we

00:35:24.190 --> 00:35:27.930
went to develop the game from
the graphic design standpoint

00:35:27.930 --> 00:35:29.380
that you want.

00:35:29.380 --> 00:35:31.970
One thing that we
don't do is--

00:35:31.970 --> 00:35:33.430
and that goes back to
the [INAUDIBLE]

00:35:33.430 --> 00:35:34.100
collaboration--

00:35:34.100 --> 00:35:38.850
is I actually don't believe in
the design by committee.

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:41.700
So when we do graphic design and
things like that, we have

00:35:41.700 --> 00:35:43.040
an art director.

00:35:43.040 --> 00:35:44.100
We discuss together.

00:35:44.100 --> 00:35:46.310
We discussed in the company, but
there's someone that makes

00:35:46.310 --> 00:35:46.670
the decision.

00:35:46.670 --> 00:35:49.860
And that someone is me, because
I'm the one who is

00:35:49.860 --> 00:35:53.520
paying for this mistake if we
screw up, and we don't sell

00:35:53.520 --> 00:35:56.550
the board game as well as
I thought we would.

00:35:56.550 --> 00:35:59.500
So we inform the game designers,
and we show them

00:35:59.500 --> 00:36:01.070
who we're going to work
with, and so on.

00:36:01.070 --> 00:36:02.800
But it's not really
collaborative in that we don't

00:36:02.800 --> 00:36:04.930
let them decide which
[INAUDIBLE] they are

00:36:04.930 --> 00:36:06.080
going to work with.

00:36:06.080 --> 00:36:07.802
All the things like that.

00:36:07.802 --> 00:36:08.190
OK?

00:36:08.190 --> 00:36:13.430
Now, from a gameplay standpoint,
depending on the

00:36:13.430 --> 00:36:14.650
game, it can be very
interactive.

00:36:14.650 --> 00:36:18.160
So if we take a game like
"Memoir 44," Richard Borg

00:36:18.160 --> 00:36:19.580
developed that game,
and designed a

00:36:19.580 --> 00:36:26.260
great game about the--

00:36:26.260 --> 00:36:26.710
Sorry.

00:36:26.710 --> 00:36:27.880
My mind goes blank.

00:36:27.880 --> 00:36:30.730
He had designed a great game
about the Civil War.

00:36:30.730 --> 00:36:32.790
And we went to him, and we said,
we'd like to do a game

00:36:32.790 --> 00:36:34.030
on World War II.

00:36:34.030 --> 00:36:37.510
And we spent the better part of
six months working with him

00:36:37.510 --> 00:36:39.970
on the game design itself,
tweaking the game design that

00:36:39.970 --> 00:36:43.180
he had to make it work
for World War II.

00:36:43.180 --> 00:36:43.610
OK?

00:36:43.610 --> 00:36:45.620
So it runs the whole gamut.

00:36:45.620 --> 00:36:48.270
Now, regarding "Ticket to Ride,"
the way we stumbled on

00:36:48.270 --> 00:36:51.620
"Ticket to Ride" is we went to
a small board game conference

00:36:51.620 --> 00:36:53.180
in Baltimore that is
held every year.

00:36:53.180 --> 00:36:54.710
And now it's moved
to Lancaster,

00:36:54.710 --> 00:36:55.330
Pennsylvania, I think.

00:36:55.330 --> 00:36:58.670
It's called the World Board
Game Championship.

00:36:58.670 --> 00:37:00.550
It's kind of a misnomer to call
it the World Board Game

00:37:00.550 --> 00:37:01.130
Championship.

00:37:01.130 --> 00:37:03.870
We tend to think of it as
the Baltimore Board Game

00:37:03.870 --> 00:37:09.550
Championship, because 95% of the
people there are in close

00:37:09.550 --> 00:37:10.750
proximity of the convention.

00:37:10.750 --> 00:37:13.220
But it's a great conventional
where people go and play games

00:37:13.220 --> 00:37:18.000
competitively for a week
of time every summer.

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:19.120
And we met with Alan there.

00:37:19.120 --> 00:37:20.290
We'd never met with
him before.

00:37:20.290 --> 00:37:21.930
It was Mark and myself.

00:37:21.930 --> 00:37:23.440
And we said, let
me [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:23.440 --> 00:37:25.210
And he said, oh, I have these
game that I need to show you.

00:37:25.210 --> 00:37:27.390
And he pulled this small
cardboard box, and it says

00:37:27.390 --> 00:37:30.200
"Station to Station." And he put
the map on the table that

00:37:30.200 --> 00:37:32.170
looked like a cool version
of the original

00:37:32.170 --> 00:37:33.680
"Ticket to Ride" map.

00:37:33.680 --> 00:37:34.770
And we started playing
the game.

00:37:34.770 --> 00:37:36.050
He said, OK, so it's
a very simple game.

00:37:36.050 --> 00:37:37.780
Here are the rules.

00:37:37.780 --> 00:37:39.650
And so we started playing two or
three times with Mark, and

00:37:39.650 --> 00:37:41.980
we look at each other,
and we're like,

00:37:41.980 --> 00:37:43.130
yes, this feels good.

00:37:43.130 --> 00:37:43.800
And so then [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:43.800 --> 00:37:47.410
Alan just wipes off of the whole
map clean and said, OK,

00:37:47.410 --> 00:37:48.790
so you understand
how it plays.

00:37:48.790 --> 00:37:51.440
So you can take it
home and decide.

00:37:51.440 --> 00:37:55.025
And with Mark, we just said,
like, you just stopped the

00:37:55.025 --> 00:37:55.390
whole game.

00:37:55.390 --> 00:37:56.090
You just destroyed
our whole game.

00:37:56.090 --> 00:37:57.360
We were playing!

00:37:57.360 --> 00:37:59.780
What did you do?

00:37:59.780 --> 00:38:03.640
And to this day, to this day,
I'm not quite sure whether

00:38:03.640 --> 00:38:06.320
Alan used that as a genius
marketing trick to really make

00:38:06.320 --> 00:38:09.050
sure he had hooked us as
a publisher, or not.

00:38:09.050 --> 00:38:11.850
Now, Alan will claim, if you ask
him in public, Alan will

00:38:11.850 --> 00:38:15.960
claim no recollection whatsoever
of ever wiping that

00:38:15.960 --> 00:38:17.590
board clean.

00:38:17.590 --> 00:38:21.270
But that's kind of the
background story behind

00:38:21.270 --> 00:38:21.790
"Ticket to Ride."

00:38:21.790 --> 00:38:23.960
And what was fun with that, and
that's true of all board

00:38:23.960 --> 00:38:26.190
games, is that I then traveled
with that little prototype.

00:38:26.190 --> 00:38:30.120
I actually flew to Korea because
back in 2004, there

00:38:30.120 --> 00:38:32.275
was kind of this board
game craze in

00:38:32.275 --> 00:38:33.690
coffee shops in Korea.

00:38:33.690 --> 00:38:35.160
And I wanted to witness
that first hand.

00:38:35.160 --> 00:38:38.600
And so I traveled with
that small prototype.

00:38:38.600 --> 00:38:39.740
And what I saw there--

00:38:39.740 --> 00:38:41.790
and I've seen it again and again
with board games-- is

00:38:41.790 --> 00:38:45.070
what's interesting is board
games, if they're really good,

00:38:45.070 --> 00:38:47.350
they will work anywhere
in the world.

00:38:47.350 --> 00:38:49.380
So no matter whether you speak
the language of the people you

00:38:49.380 --> 00:38:51.040
play with or not, you can
have a great time.

00:38:51.040 --> 00:38:51.940
And we saw that.

00:38:51.940 --> 00:38:53.480
Landed in Korea.

00:38:53.480 --> 00:38:55.960
Quickly was in a cafe where I
have no clue what people were

00:38:55.960 --> 00:38:56.960
talking about.

00:38:56.960 --> 00:38:57.330
OK?

00:38:57.330 --> 00:38:58.740
I couldn't understand a word,
and they probably couldn't

00:38:58.740 --> 00:38:59.580
understand a word.

00:38:59.580 --> 00:39:01.600
You guys probably don't
understand half of the words

00:39:01.600 --> 00:39:03.660
I've been talking about.

00:39:03.660 --> 00:39:06.830
And I called Mark, and I said,
you know, this game

00:39:06.830 --> 00:39:08.570
is going to be big.

00:39:08.570 --> 00:39:10.420
We knew right then.

00:39:10.420 --> 00:39:12.920
So that's one of the nice things
about the prototypes is

00:39:12.920 --> 00:39:17.760
again, even if you have really
bad graphics, you'll know very

00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:21.345
quickly, once you play with
people, whether you have a

00:39:21.345 --> 00:39:22.620
winner or not.

00:39:22.620 --> 00:39:24.940
AUDIENCE: So first of, I wanted
to thank you very much.

00:39:24.940 --> 00:39:28.300
I absolutely love "Ticket to
Ride." I actually bought a

00:39:28.300 --> 00:39:30.360
copy for my family back home in
Chicago, and they've been

00:39:30.360 --> 00:39:33.270
playing it like every day for
the past several months.

00:39:33.270 --> 00:39:35.050
ERIC HAUTEMONT: Thank you.

00:39:35.050 --> 00:39:37.688
Thank you or sorry?

00:39:37.688 --> 00:39:40.090
AUDIENCE: Oh, it's more of
a thank you, actually.

00:39:40.090 --> 00:39:41.860
It helped me survive
a few trips home,

00:39:41.860 --> 00:39:43.900
which is always nice.

00:39:43.900 --> 00:39:47.340
One thing I noticed in
particular, because I play the

00:39:47.340 --> 00:39:50.000
tablet version a lot, is that
when you play the tablet

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:53.070
version, it tends to be more of
a single player experience,

00:39:53.070 --> 00:39:57.160
even when you're
playing online.

00:39:57.160 --> 00:40:01.160
Because your goal is to kind
of finish your routes.

00:40:01.160 --> 00:40:04.780
Where when you're playing in
person, there's more of this

00:40:04.780 --> 00:40:07.140
competitive edge, where you kind
of want to screw people

00:40:07.140 --> 00:40:08.900
over, and you want
to cut them off.

00:40:08.900 --> 00:40:11.250
And you want to kind of see
where they're trying to get

00:40:11.250 --> 00:40:13.940
to, and cause more mayhem.

00:40:13.940 --> 00:40:19.150
Is there any way of kind of
adding that into the digital

00:40:19.150 --> 00:40:21.490
version of the game?

00:40:21.490 --> 00:40:25.440
I just found that even though
I play both copies, that my

00:40:25.440 --> 00:40:28.740
strategy changes from
game to play.

00:40:28.740 --> 00:40:29.870
ERIC HAUTEMONT: What you
say is very true.

00:40:29.870 --> 00:40:32.050
I think it's very tough on a
game like "Ticket to Ride."

00:40:32.050 --> 00:40:35.000
And the reason for that, and
that's something that's shared

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:36.630
with a lot of board game
designs, is that there's

00:40:36.630 --> 00:40:38.030
hidden information.

00:40:38.030 --> 00:40:40.450
And so because you have it, that
hidden information, it's

00:40:40.450 --> 00:40:43.460
very difficult for us to have
a commercially practical

00:40:43.460 --> 00:40:46.330
version where you could play
"Ticket to Ride" sharing the

00:40:46.330 --> 00:40:49.320
same tablet as your digital
board with other people

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:50.850
sitting across from you.

00:40:50.850 --> 00:40:51.810
OK?

00:40:51.810 --> 00:40:54.830
And until we get that, so that
means we have to assume, then,

00:40:54.830 --> 00:40:58.260
that everybody has a phone,
too, that they can use, to

00:40:58.260 --> 00:40:59.100
hold in their hand.

00:40:59.100 --> 00:41:00.570
And then you have to
deal with all these

00:41:00.570 --> 00:41:02.620
interface issues of, OK--

00:41:02.620 --> 00:41:04.620
Again, the real world
is complex, or it's

00:41:04.620 --> 00:41:06.380
simpler than it looks.

00:41:06.380 --> 00:41:09.070
So when you have real cards in
your hand, you just drop you

00:41:09.070 --> 00:41:10.530
cards, and you're done.

00:41:10.530 --> 00:41:12.370
If you have a digital device
in your hand, and you're

00:41:12.370 --> 00:41:14.780
trying to drop those cards onto
the digital device in the

00:41:14.780 --> 00:41:17.140
middle, it gets quickly
pretty awkward.

00:41:17.140 --> 00:41:19.440
And you have to worry about your
Bluetooth connection or

00:41:19.440 --> 00:41:21.910
your Wi-Fi connection dropping
off, and all kinds of crap

00:41:21.910 --> 00:41:23.220
that you don't have to
worry about with a

00:41:23.220 --> 00:41:24.485
real deck of cards.

00:41:24.485 --> 00:41:24.800
OK?

00:41:24.800 --> 00:41:27.000
So for games with hidden
information like "Ticket to

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:31.650
Ride," I'd say it's very
difficult until the technology

00:41:31.650 --> 00:41:33.020
gets a lot more transparent.

00:41:33.020 --> 00:41:35.950
Now, with games like "Small
World," you can actually play

00:41:35.950 --> 00:41:38.520
a game of "Small World" face
to face around the tablet.

00:41:38.520 --> 00:41:41.930
And in that case, we actually
see the behavior on the type

00:41:41.930 --> 00:41:44.925
of play very much being the
same, with the kind of

00:41:44.925 --> 00:41:47.310
aggressiveness you describe,
and so on.

00:41:47.310 --> 00:41:51.950
What's interesting is we run a
"Ticket to Ride" tournament,

00:41:51.950 --> 00:41:53.220
championship tournament.

00:41:53.220 --> 00:41:55.490
Real "Ticket to Ride" with
the real board game.

00:41:55.490 --> 00:41:57.930
And because we have people that
have played 80,000 games,

00:41:57.930 --> 00:42:01.000
where lots of people online that
think like, they're the

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:02.790
king of "Ticket to Ride," and
nobody can beat them.

00:42:02.790 --> 00:42:05.220
So when we started doing
national qualifications for

00:42:05.220 --> 00:42:09.390
that tournament, we had lots
of people who said, I'm so

00:42:09.390 --> 00:42:10.560
good online.

00:42:10.560 --> 00:42:12.420
I'm not even going to go
for the qualifiers.

00:42:12.420 --> 00:42:14.623
I'm just going to go in the
actual competition, and I'm

00:42:14.623 --> 00:42:15.810
going to crush everyone.

00:42:15.810 --> 00:42:18.460
And I'd say over 90% of people
that had that kind of

00:42:18.460 --> 00:42:21.400
attitude, got their clock
cleaned when they actually

00:42:21.400 --> 00:42:24.000
played the real, physical
board game.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:24.410
OK?

00:42:24.410 --> 00:42:26.570
Because it plays different.

00:42:26.570 --> 00:42:27.820
It really does.

00:42:27.820 --> 00:42:30.890
And we had the final where
we had one person--

00:42:30.890 --> 00:42:31.430
it was interesting.

00:42:31.430 --> 00:42:33.860
We had the final where we had
one best one that actually

00:42:33.860 --> 00:42:37.490
played a lot of physical board
game versions of "Ticket to

00:42:37.490 --> 00:42:38.160
Ride."

00:42:38.160 --> 00:42:40.330
And we had this opponent, who
was the opposite of my

00:42:40.330 --> 00:42:43.190
finalist, who was actually a
professional player, in that

00:42:43.190 --> 00:42:45.100
he didn't really particularly
care, at the time, about

00:42:45.100 --> 00:42:47.640
"Ticket to Ride." He cares about
playing tournaments with

00:42:47.640 --> 00:42:49.140
money to win.

00:42:49.140 --> 00:42:52.590
And he studies the game, and
he just goes after that.

00:42:52.590 --> 00:42:56.080
And so he had only played like
five games of "Ticket to Ride"

00:42:56.080 --> 00:42:58.670
in real life, and a couple
of games online.

00:42:58.670 --> 00:43:01.420
But he'd studied all about the
ticket distribution, and

00:43:01.420 --> 00:43:02.700
everything else.

00:43:02.700 --> 00:43:04.190
And he finished second.

00:43:04.190 --> 00:43:07.250
So I guess experience
does pay off.

00:43:07.250 --> 00:43:10.950
But it shows there's
different sides.

00:43:10.950 --> 00:43:13.280
To us, that's part of what's
fun, is what you get out of

00:43:13.280 --> 00:43:15.830
playing online tends to be
different from what you get

00:43:15.830 --> 00:43:17.700
out of playing the physical
board game.

00:43:17.700 --> 00:43:19.880
And so eventually, you
end up buying both,

00:43:19.880 --> 00:43:22.531
which we love you for.

00:43:22.531 --> 00:43:23.320
MALE SPEAKER: All right.

00:43:23.320 --> 00:43:25.010
We just have time for a
couple more questions.

00:43:25.010 --> 00:43:27.077
There's one from VC, and
then we're going to

00:43:27.077 --> 00:43:28.300
take one over here.

00:43:28.300 --> 00:43:30.690
So one from VC from Henry.

00:43:30.690 --> 00:43:34.480
He asks, "Given your emphasis
on simplicity of design, how

00:43:34.480 --> 00:43:36.980
do you feel about the recent
popularity of really complex

00:43:36.980 --> 00:43:40.660
games, like 'Fantas.y Flight,"
coming out of "Fantasy

00:43:40.660 --> 00:43:44.380
Flight," like "Civilization,"
"Ora et Labora?"

00:43:44.380 --> 00:43:50.080
ERIC HAUTEMONT: So I think it's
interesting that the more

00:43:50.080 --> 00:43:51.700
complex games can be
very exciting.

00:43:51.700 --> 00:43:53.410
And it's interesting you
mentioned "Civilization,"

00:43:53.410 --> 00:43:58.460
because the old Avalon Hill
"Advanced Civilization" is

00:43:58.460 --> 00:44:01.170
kind of the all-time favorite
of mine, even though I would

00:44:01.170 --> 00:44:02.950
never publish it as
a board game.

00:44:02.950 --> 00:44:05.770
I have memories of playing down
the block, literally, for

00:44:05.770 --> 00:44:09.520
like 14 hours in a row.

00:44:09.520 --> 00:44:12.540
And that's some of
my best memories.

00:44:12.540 --> 00:44:17.230
I think the difference between
the long games, or the simple

00:44:17.230 --> 00:44:20.300
games and the complex
games, is the--

00:44:20.300 --> 00:44:22.010
it goes back to the
word of mouth.

00:44:22.010 --> 00:44:25.250
The word-of-mouth factor on
the complex games is a lot

00:44:25.250 --> 00:44:27.120
harder to grow fast.

00:44:27.120 --> 00:44:28.940
And so you have a much
smaller population.

00:44:28.940 --> 00:44:30.900
So you have people that
have become, I'd

00:44:30.900 --> 00:44:32.680
say, board game literate.

00:44:32.680 --> 00:44:34.520
And so you have people that
actually-- you have a small

00:44:34.520 --> 00:44:36.470
segment of the population
that actually enjoys

00:44:36.470 --> 00:44:37.280
learning new games.

00:44:37.280 --> 00:44:40.200
And so when we go to like Alan
Moon's Gathering of Friends,

00:44:40.200 --> 00:44:42.970
there are people who are there
just to play new games.

00:44:42.970 --> 00:44:44.830
And if you propose to them to
play a game they've already

00:44:44.830 --> 00:44:46.350
played, they're going
to say, no.

00:44:46.350 --> 00:44:48.030
I actually want to
play a new game.

00:44:48.030 --> 00:44:49.920
And so there's people that
kind of enjoy that mental

00:44:49.920 --> 00:44:51.130
gymnastic, if you want.

00:44:51.130 --> 00:44:53.390
And once you get over the hump,
I can see why people

00:44:53.390 --> 00:44:54.090
enjoy that.

00:44:54.090 --> 00:44:56.366
But that's a very
small minority.

00:44:56.366 --> 00:44:58.510
AUDIENCE: So this is a slightly
different question.

00:44:58.510 --> 00:45:04.070
But you're talking about
ensuring the dice rolling in

00:45:04.070 --> 00:45:06.550
"Memoir 44," and games
like that, was fair.

00:45:06.550 --> 00:45:09.790
So I was curious as to why the
die in "Small World" has the

00:45:09.790 --> 00:45:12.640
one across from the three,
instead of having the three

00:45:12.640 --> 00:45:15.610
sides all across from blank
faces, which would have a

00:45:15.610 --> 00:45:18.641
greater guarantee of
having a fair die.

00:45:18.641 --> 00:45:21.880
ERIC HAUTEMONT: Actually,
it's a good question.

00:45:21.880 --> 00:45:25.670
Because in the game itself, that
difference, when you look

00:45:25.670 --> 00:45:28.200
at the impact of the difference,
makes no

00:45:28.200 --> 00:45:29.100
difference.

00:45:29.100 --> 00:45:31.990
So we went with whatever was
the simplest for the game,

00:45:31.990 --> 00:45:34.440
which was easiest for the shop
design, to give to the tool

00:45:34.440 --> 00:45:37.070
manufacturer to do.

00:45:37.070 --> 00:45:39.110
So that's the actual
reason why.

00:45:39.110 --> 00:45:42.490
We had a simulation when we
did that World Board Game

00:45:42.490 --> 00:45:46.950
Championship with "Ticket
to Ride." One of the two

00:45:46.950 --> 00:45:51.410
finalists came to me and said,
OK, so I looked at whether the

00:45:51.410 --> 00:45:52.620
tournament rules work.

00:45:52.620 --> 00:45:55.140
And how are we going to
decide who starts?

00:45:55.140 --> 00:46:00.090
It was the first person
to win two games.

00:46:00.090 --> 00:46:03.110
And since there's no tie, within
three games, you know

00:46:03.110 --> 00:46:04.350
what happens.

00:46:04.350 --> 00:46:06.890
And he's like, how are we going
to decide who's going to

00:46:06.890 --> 00:46:08.660
start the first game?

00:46:08.660 --> 00:46:11.440
And I looked at the guy,
and I said, say what?

00:46:11.440 --> 00:46:14.380
And he said, yeah, there's
an advantage to

00:46:14.380 --> 00:46:16.212
whoever starts first.

00:46:16.212 --> 00:46:17.700
And I said, well, yeah, there's

00:46:17.700 --> 00:46:18.650
a theoretical advantage.

00:46:18.650 --> 00:46:20.420
And the guy got like really--

00:46:20.420 --> 00:46:21.210
So we said, OK, fine.

00:46:21.210 --> 00:46:23.480
So I went to see the
other finalist.

00:46:23.480 --> 00:46:26.100
I said, OK.

00:46:26.100 --> 00:46:28.870
So that guy wants to discuss
who's going to start.

00:46:28.870 --> 00:46:31.360
And the other finalist looked at
me, and he said, that's OK.

00:46:31.360 --> 00:46:32.300
let him start.

00:46:32.300 --> 00:46:33.830
I'll just work a little
bit harder.

00:46:33.830 --> 00:46:35.790
And then he proceeded
to just crush him.

00:46:35.790 --> 00:46:39.420
And he won two games in a row.

00:46:39.420 --> 00:46:41.260
So I guess that kind of
sums up my view about

00:46:41.260 --> 00:46:43.050
those kind of things.

00:46:43.050 --> 00:46:46.000
They're kind of fun to think
up from a math standpoint.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:49.270
From a practical standpoint--

00:46:49.270 --> 00:46:54.380
I'll give you the dice
design that favors

00:46:54.380 --> 00:46:55.920
your odds any time.

00:46:55.920 --> 00:46:59.230
AUDIENCE: About the online
versus offline gaming.

00:46:59.230 --> 00:47:01.855
So in offline, one
of the biggest--

00:47:01.855 --> 00:47:04.820
the thing that I enjoy most
is pitting people

00:47:04.820 --> 00:47:05.700
against each other.

00:47:05.700 --> 00:47:07.640
And you're like, oh,
he's leading.

00:47:07.640 --> 00:47:09.090
You should attack him,
and so forth.

00:47:09.090 --> 00:47:11.900
And that like doesn't translate
to online at all.

00:47:11.900 --> 00:47:15.840
And so I've been thinking.

00:47:15.840 --> 00:47:18.325
I saw this implemented for
"Dominion." I think it's over

00:47:18.325 --> 00:47:20.330
in Google Hangouts.

00:47:20.330 --> 00:47:24.060
And letting people like see
each other, and then like

00:47:24.060 --> 00:47:25.550
encouraging that interaction.

00:47:25.550 --> 00:47:26.540
What do you think about that?

00:47:26.540 --> 00:47:29.100
Could that be?

00:47:29.100 --> 00:47:32.130
ERIC HAUTEMONT: The only thing
about that, the only

00:47:32.130 --> 00:47:33.660
reservation I have about those
kind of things-- and we

00:47:33.660 --> 00:47:34.020
[INAUDIBLE]

00:47:34.020 --> 00:47:34.240
people.

00:47:34.240 --> 00:47:36.370
That's why we don't implement
them ourselves.

00:47:36.370 --> 00:47:38.360
We let people, if they want--
and we know there's some

00:47:38.360 --> 00:47:41.260
people, sometimes, that actually
will literally open a

00:47:41.260 --> 00:47:43.920
chat channel, and just like
trash talk with each other

00:47:43.920 --> 00:47:44.830
during a game.

00:47:44.830 --> 00:47:47.220
The reason we don't support that
directly in the game--

00:47:47.220 --> 00:47:50.610
besides the fact that it's work
that we'd rather spend on

00:47:50.610 --> 00:47:52.170
designing other games--

00:47:52.170 --> 00:47:54.530
so what I want to say is we're
always leery of things that

00:47:54.530 --> 00:47:56.170
remove transparency.

00:47:56.170 --> 00:47:58.820
We think it's already such a
challenge to translate a

00:47:58.820 --> 00:48:00.940
physical board game
properly online.

00:48:00.940 --> 00:48:07.560
That the more tools, the more
technology you add, it's very

00:48:07.560 --> 00:48:09.370
difficult to do that in a way
that is really transparent.

00:48:09.370 --> 00:48:11.990
So even though when I'm playing
in real life, it's

00:48:11.990 --> 00:48:14.930
very easy for me to do some
trash talk, if I have to go

00:48:14.930 --> 00:48:16.730
and actually type that,
we think that's a big

00:48:16.730 --> 00:48:17.470
distraction.

00:48:17.470 --> 00:48:19.090
And that's not a very
transparent way of

00:48:19.090 --> 00:48:20.630
communicating with people.

00:48:20.630 --> 00:48:24.400
And so that's the other reason
why we don't care so much

00:48:24.400 --> 00:48:25.120
about those kinds of things.

00:48:25.120 --> 00:48:29.010
We're really striving for, I
think, the technology not

00:48:29.010 --> 00:48:29.660
getting in the way.

00:48:29.660 --> 00:48:32.050
I mean, that's one thing that is
fascinating to us, being in

00:48:32.050 --> 00:48:34.390
Silicon Valley, there's
all these people--

00:48:34.390 --> 00:48:36.700
Every three months, there's
someone who's come out with a

00:48:36.700 --> 00:48:37.870
new dice design.

00:48:37.870 --> 00:48:38.710
And they go, Look.

00:48:38.710 --> 00:48:41.130
There's this superduper
electronic dice, and it's got

00:48:41.130 --> 00:48:42.250
a USB connection.

00:48:42.250 --> 00:48:45.370
It's got a hard drive in it, and
it does all these things.

00:48:45.370 --> 00:48:49.500
I'm like, dice have worked fine
for thousands of years.

00:48:49.500 --> 00:48:50.390
OK?

00:48:50.390 --> 00:48:52.340
What's the point?

00:48:52.340 --> 00:48:53.750
And so we try and--

00:48:53.750 --> 00:48:59.020
On the one hand, we look at
new technology, and we're

00:48:59.020 --> 00:49:02.275
really curious to see what
happens with Google Glasses in

00:49:02.275 --> 00:49:04.730
terms of certain types of hidden
information that we

00:49:04.730 --> 00:49:07.910
think it could take care
of during the games.

00:49:07.910 --> 00:49:10.340
At the same time, we're really
careful to go slow, and not do

00:49:10.340 --> 00:49:12.940
things that are non-transparent,
and really

00:49:12.940 --> 00:49:16.480
become more cumbersome, and
remove more than they add.

00:49:16.480 --> 00:49:18.560
MALE SPEAKER: Let's give Eric
a big round of applause.

00:49:18.560 --> 00:49:20.884
[APPLAUSE]

00:49:20.884 --> 00:49:22.470
ERIC HAUTEMONT: Thank you.

00:49:22.470 --> 00:49:22.920
Thank you.

00:49:22.920 --> 00:49:24.420
MALE SPEAKER: Thanks
again for coming.

